The Status of Just Walk Out
---------------------------

From The Information ( https://www.theinformation.com/articles/amazons-groc=
ery-stores-to-drop-just-walk-out-checkout-tech ) :

Amazon=E2=80=99s grab-and-go checkout system, Just Walk Out, has been a cen=
terpiece of its ambitions to transform bricks-and-mortar supermarkets. Now =
Amazon is gearing up to open a new batch of grocery stores after an 18-mont=
h pause=E2=80=94and it=E2=80=99s ditching the technology.

Tony Hoggett, Amazon=E2=80=99s senior vice president of grocery stores, sai=
d in an interview that the next generation of Amazon Fresh stores, the comm=
erce giant=E2=80=99s answer to mass-market grocery chains, will focus inste=
ad on offering Dash Carts, which let customers scan items while they shop. =
This year, Amazon will also revamp the majority of its existing Fresh locat=
ions into =E2=80=9Cversion two=E2=80=9D stores, Hoggett said, removing Just=
 Walk Out where it=E2=80=99s already installed while sprucing up the stores=
 across the board.

Amazon=E2=80=99s pullback on deploying Just Walk Out underscores how the co=
mpany is still fine-tuning its broader grocery strategy. It also shows the =
limitations of using Just Walk Out, which relies on cameras and sensors to =
track what people leave the store with, in larger-format stores. Amazon had=
 previously tried to pitch big-box retailers like Woolworths on the technol=
ogy and even weighed opening its own big-box stores ( https://www.theinform=
ation.com/articles/how-amazons-bricks-and-mortar-dreams-hit-a-wall ) equipp=
ed with Just Walk Out, The Information has reported.

Much of the initial reaction to this news was driven by this Gizmodo story =
( https://gizmodo.com/amazon-reportedly-ditches-just-walk-out-grocery-store=
s-1851381116 ) :

Amazon is phasing out its checkout-less grocery stores with =E2=80=9CJust W=
alk Out=E2=80=9D technology, first reported by The Information Tuesday. The=
 company=E2=80=99s senior vice president of grocery stores says they=E2=80=
=99re moving away from Just Walk Out, which relied on cameras and sensors t=
o track what people were leaving the store with.

Just over half of Amazon Fresh stores are equipped with Just Walk Out. The =
technology allows customers to skip checkout altogether by scanning a QR co=
de when they enter the store. Though it seemed completely automated, Just W=
alk Out relied on more than 1,000 people in India watching and labeling vid=
eos to ensure accurate checkouts. The cashiers were simply moved off-site, =
and they watched you as you shopped.

I regret latching onto this story in Friday=E2=80=99s Dithering ( https://d=
ithering.fm/ ) , although I did include the caveat that those workers in In=
dia were just as likely to be doing verification and error correction than =
they were to be actually calculating every transaction. That does appear to=
 be the case, which makes sense: any sort of machine learning system needs =
feedback mechanisms to improve over time, although it does appear that =E2=
=80=9CJust Walk Out=E2=80=9D wasn=E2=80=99t improving =E2=80=94 or more imp=
ortantly, scaling =E2=80=94 to the extent that Amazon hoped.

This blog post from Sucharita Kodali at Forrester ( https://www.forrester.c=
om/blogs/no-amazon-isnt-killing-just-walk-out-but-rather-pushing-hard-in-it=
/ ) , meanwhile, has the complete opposite spin on the news:

A number of media articles this week cited that Amazon was removing its Jus=
t Walk Out solution from Amazon Fresh grocery stores. It turned out to be a=
 bad game of telephone tag stemming from an interview with Tony Hoggett, he=
ad of Amazon=E2=80=99s physical grocery store endeavors, conducted by The I=
nformation. Even The Information=E2=80=99s paywall didn=E2=80=99t stop indu=
stry insiders from riffing on the supposed demise of JWO and its expensive =
cost.

I talked to Jon =E2=80=9CJJ=E2=80=9D Jenkins, a senior executive who worked=
 for years with =E2=80=9CJeff B.=E2=80=9D and is on the team at Amazon Web =
Services that runs Just Walk Out (aka =E2=80=9CJWO,=E2=80=9D which they als=
o affectionately call J-Wo, like J-Lo). He clarified several points=E2=80=
=A6

Those points were:

* Amazon is still investing in Just Walk Out for smaller format stores in p=
laces like sports arenas and airports.
* The =E2=80=9C1,000 Indians=E2=80=9D were in fact working to improve the m=
achine learnings algorithms for new stores in particular.
* The goal of the interview with The Information was to emphasize that the =
Dash Cart concept was actually better for larger stores.

I find this story credible. By far my best personal experience with =E2=80=
=9CJust Walk Out=E2=80=9D was at the United Center stadium in Chicago last =
fall: it was so much faster and more convenient to walk into the Amazon sto=
re to grab a bottle of soda than to wait in line for concessions; moreover,=
 the prices in stadiums (and airports) are so high for such a low cost item=
 that I can imagine there is a lot of latitude for mistakes and/or leakage.=
 And, by the same token, I can see why Just Walk Out didn=E2=80=99t work wi=
th larger scale concepts, which differ in two important ways: first, the nu=
mber of items to be tracked is far larger, and second, the margins are much=
 lower.

