When Hoggett joined Amazon, he inherited a scattershot variety of bricks-an=
d-mortar projects ranging from Whole Foods, Fresh and Amazon Go convenience=
 stores to books, clothing and variety stores. Amazon has since shuttered v=
irtually all of its nongrocery physical stores, part of broader cost cuttin=
g across the company, and has taken steps to integrate grocery store teams =
that had been separate when Hoggett arrived, he said. That=E2=80=99s meant =
combining teams that had been working on functions like supply chains and r=
eal estate separately for Amazon.com, Fresh, Go and Whole Foods, Hoggett sa=
id.

That consolidation extends to Amazon=E2=80=99s approach to delivery, demons=
trated by an automated fulfillment center the company just opened outside N=
ew York in Bethpage, Long Island. That facility processes online orders for=
 Amazon Fresh and will eventually add Whole Foods and popular grocery produ=
cts from Amazon.com, Hoggett said. The idea is to eventually let Amazon sho=
ppers purchase items from any of its grocery banners, as well as from outsi=
de retailers that partner with Amazon, and then have all the items arrive i=
n a single delivery.

Hoggett is also experimenting with changes to how Amazon handles deliveries=
 from existing stores, including opening a 20,000-square-foot automated mic=
rofulfillment center inside a Whole Foods store later this year, he said. B=
oth the Bethpage warehouse and the Whole Foods microfulfillment center will=
 help Amazon pack online orders more efficiently and make the in-store shop=
ping experience cleaner and more appealing for customers, he said. Once the=
 facilities are fully up and running, the idea is that any automated facili=
ty will be able to take over the delivery volume that five nearby stores ha=
d previously handled, according to Hoggett.

These two approaches are the exact opposite! I don=E2=80=99t hate it, thoug=
h: Amazon is still experimenting, and just because some of those experiment=
s fail is, paradoxically, the sign of a successful culture. At the same tim=
e, it=E2=80=99s still not clear that anything that doesn=E2=80=99t scale wi=
ll ever ultimately make sense for Amazon, and that may include groceries as=
 well.

TSMC Gets CHIPS Act Grant
-------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-04-08/tsmc-ge=
ts-11-6-billion-in-us-grants-loans-for-three-chip-fabs ) :

The US plans to award Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. $6.6 billion i=
n grants and as much as $5 billion in loans to help the world=E2=80=99s top=
 chipmaker build factories in Arizona, expanding President Joe Biden=E2=80=
=99s effort to boost domestic production of critical technology. Under the =
preliminary agreement announced by the US on Monday, TSMC will construct a =
third factory in Phoenix, adding to two facilities in the state that are ex=
pected to begin production in 2025 and 2028. In total, the package will sup=
port more than $65 billion in investments at the three plants by TSMC, the =
go-to chipmaker for companies such as Apple Inc. and Nvidia Corp.

TSMC=E2=80=99s third fabrication site, or fab, will rely on next-generation=
 2-nanometer process technology, and is slated to be operational before the=
 end of the decade. US Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo said the 2nm chips =
are essential to emerging technologies including artificial intelligence, a=
s well as for the military.

This news isn=E2=80=99t a big surprise, particularly after Global Foundries=
, Intel, and Samsung all received CHIPS Act packages; I do think the commit=
ment to a third fab in Arizona is, though, a big win for the Biden administ=
ration, as it increases the likelihood of the Arizona site becoming a meani=
ngful production center for TSMC, as opposed to a bare-minimum sop to U.S. =
political demands and TSMC=E2=80=99s biggest customers ( https://stratecher=
y.com/2022/tsmc-in-arizona-arizona-challenges-realities-and-motivations/?ac=
cess_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubG=
luZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJh=
enAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF=
0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIyL3RzbWMtaW4tYXJpem9uYS1hcml6b25hLWNoYWxsZW5nZXMtcmVhbG=
l0aWVzLWFuZC1tb3RpdmF0aW9ucy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcxNTE3MzE1OCwiaWF0IjoxNzEyNTgxM=
TU4LCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZl=
ZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW5=
0cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.nNCPWS8=
MdtOVd-TON8qAnI6Xgct6LQi9qQqtOLgiN1P1NjHb1bG8kNMgzpR4-7vozGNMQn-qLVcehaELRw=
LNrhvjy84ztHo96btQc30XufYOqqNW9_4hotOqecMilzK83wfD76atJqX9uGRnsrN3y90U28e8t=
JifTZT-jGRb2R5iWMRPuQxa8nvibcstAX-78uoasBkBfXdgcl7ShWkz_BScUpSQwVgG1sO18aao=
wEuJ37xw_61w0JKAk0KGQ6SsMpDFXEFw7CQkA42gUMcZb63W6GVp_KDMyPdw6WSKN4e_3VDk4ju=
AFuNB9jP8_MItmXoCdE48poMtgfWakgWaPg ). At the same time, it=E2=80=99s worth=
 pointing out that TSMC is planning to start manufacturing 2nm chips in vol=
ume in Taiwan next year ( https://www.techpowerup.com/319301/tsmc-2-nm-node=
-to-enter-risk-production-in-q4-2024-mass-production-in-q2-2025-if-all-goes=
-well ) ; having the same process technology in the U.S. =E2=80=9Cbefore th=
e end of the decade=E2=80=9D is nice but still behind.

This announcement also follows on the heels of several other relevant piece=
s of news:

* Amkor is building a packaging and testing plant ( https://www.azcentral.c=
om/story/money/business/tech/2023/11/30/amkor-build-semiconductor-testing-p=
lant-peoria-2000-jobs/71752922007/ ) in Arizona that will be primarily focu=
sed on Apple chips produced by TSMC down the road. This was an essential mi=
ssing piece of the story in terms of de-risking from Taiwan, and emphasizes=
 the role that Apple has likely played in this entire saga.
* TSMC officially opened a new trailing edge fab in Japan ( https://www.blo=
omberg.com/news/articles/2024-02-22/tsmc-sony-help-japan-pull-off-an-early-=
victory-in-the-race-to-make-more-chips ) , and is building more.
* TSMC is building a trailing edge fab in Germany ( https://pr.tsmc.com/eng=
lish/news/3049 ) ; construction will begin in Dresden later this year, and =
will enter production in 2027.

The last two notes address a key concern I had about the CHIPS Act ( https:=
//stratechery.com/2022/chips-and-china/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIs=
ImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOi=
