XVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.u0GaXKmFYjx8PzRR5rTUt5XkQ=
bSbUwh_pGMIs_xFbbr73iKI-b_FW-KXR29KCS4T9djotu9GaXY_m9P5TJKZw6VGiPeHj4n4CpFl=
tPAFZI81adHPjhKhxtsjUXrvwaw1e3Jx-vQ23xPNoWhKFwjmVZY5jzAELCQADqF8LIvUQX8X1B1=
iCQuTwBUr1dbuRF6r108PWM8Zb4YIYuTsDrizMpLILQ4t7gnIYicyOdp3JhKE6jljSlFrBoradb=
WFpVES2VzYrE-fbqvKqbqeebfaCssUY7bT5f8p6BMClRHxzfdr6gPstgjMMtg3VowhVhHNoPPxP=
aTNv1bP3UpDPx2ayg ) : China already had the capability of building trailing=
 edge chips, which meant they could potentially corner the market if TSMC=
=E2=80=99s Taiwan fabs were inaccessible for whatever reason. These expansi=
ons in Japan and Germany, though, start to address that need, leaving the U=
.S. to focus more on the leading edge.

None of this will ever fully address that worst-case outcome, to be clear; =
it would be basically impossible =E2=80=94 and economically foolish =E2=80=
=94 to fully remove Taiwan from the semiconductor value chain, and TSMC and=
 the Taiwanese government don=E2=80=99t want that to happen anyways. Howeve=
r, having at least some sort of foundation from which to build elsewhere in=
 the world, in case of that worst-case scenario, is prudent for both Wester=
n governments, tech companies, and TSMC.

